player.seasonOutlook: In a reserve role behind Ivica Zubac on the Clippers, Plumlee doesn't appear to have a path to a high number of minutes. He averaged 7.5 PPG, 7.0 RPG, and 1.7 APG in 20.0 MPG after being traded to Los Angeles last season. You can expect similar statistical production from Plumlee this upcoming season.

It remains to be seen whether Isaac will be able to contribute to this young Magic team with playoff aspirations. Since 2020, he has played in only 14 games. His defensive and rebounding abilities make him a valuable asset for Orlando, even as he continues to work his way back. After undergoing left abductor surgery, Isaac hopes to be ready for training camp and is motivated to prove himself. Last season, he played 11 games and averaged 5.0 PPG, 4.0 RPG and 1.3 SPG in 11.3 MPG. Isaac has a very high fantasy ceiling if given consistent minutes, but his durability makes him difficult to trust.

Biyombo led the Suns with 88 blocks despite only averaging 14.3 MPG last season. Although he's a great rebounder and shot-blocker, his offensive performance is lacking and he's only a big factor if Jusuf Nurkic misses time.

Kuminga remains one of the faces of the Warriors next-generation plans after being drafted in the lottery of the 2021 NBA draft. The Warriors moved on from Jordan Poole and James Whiteman, but Kuminga remains. He has maintained a role as the seventh-eighth man in their rotations for large swathes of time, though there have also been periods when he has fallen out of the rotation completely. The Warriors enter this season with Draymond Green missing time due an ankle injury, so Kuminga has a chance to show himself worthy of bigger minutes. If he does so, he has upside to average in the mid-teens as a scorer in closer to starter minutes.
